This RMP is submitted by CEREX Advanced Fabrics, Inc. for its nylon nonwoven manufacturing process which uses a regulated substance, anhydrous Hydrogen Chloride (aHCl). This nonwoven manufacturing process has been in continuous operation since January, 1970. The process was originally developed by Monsanto Company in the late '60s and operated by Monsanto until sold to James River Corporation in September, 1985. Since 1985, the ownership of the nylon nonwoven manufacturing operation changed through several corporate owners, and then became privately held as CEREX Advanced Fabrics (CEREX) in 1994. The covered process includes a single piping system that continuously delivers Anhydrous Hydrogen Chloride from one of three tube trailers to a single injection point where the material is mixed and substantially diluted for use as a process aid to bond nylon fibers to form a fabric. The covered process also includes a vent system used to evacuate and purge the process piping to a "drowning jet" whereby the material is diluted and neutralized.



A. Accidental release prevention and emergency response policies:

o PRRMPHCL001: Pensacola Cerex Plant Emergency Management Program for the HCl Process Master Program Document;

    This procedure outlines and summarizes all Cerex internal systems and documentation related to the operation and maintenance of the above listed covered process, meeting all requirements established by OSHA/EPA for highly hazardous chemicals.

o PRSFTY009: HCl Emergency Procedure Document;

    The purpose of this procedure is to outline proper response by any Cerex Advanced Fabrics employee to a release of Hydrogen Chloride

o RM034: HCl Emergency Decision Tree for Operations;

    The purpose of this flowchart is to outline proper response by any Cerex Advanced Fabrics employee to a release and/or indication of a release of Hydrogen Chloride

